data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your expression-tree construction **won't compile**. Replace it with the much simpler inline lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — now auto-uniquified + full path for nested

**Two sub-changes:**

| Scenario | EF Core 9 column | EF Core 10 column |
|---|---|---|
| `ShippingAddress.Street` / `BillingAddress.Street` | Both → `Street` (silent collision!) | `Street` and `Street1` |
| `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` (nested) | `BillingAddress_City` | `Payment_BillingAddress_City` |

This **will generate a migration** that renames columns. To keep old names and avoid a migration, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types — pin to the old (short) name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> ⚠️ If you *were* relying on the old collision behavior (two properties sharing one column), you **must** add explicit `HasColumnName` calls or you'll get schema drift.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Update your signature:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (may have constants redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Apply this to **all** methods you implement (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
